<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1911-03-08T18:36:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1911-03-08T18:36:00-05:00" n="567" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d567">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/898.</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Chargé
                                    d’Affaires</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Mexico</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1911-03-08T17:00:00-06:36"><hi rend="italic">March 8,
                                        1911—5 p.m.</hi></date></dateline></opener>
                        <p>Department’s March 7, 10 p.m. Minister for foreign affairs much gratified
                            to have President’s assurance, but states no misgivings were
                            entertained. The mobilization is to-day the preponderating topic in all
                            circles, the general opinion being that it has some ulterior
                            purpose.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Dearing.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>